SIMPLE: utterance
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Utterance
<hw>Ut"ter*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of uttering.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>Sale by offering to the public.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Putting in circulation; <as>as, the
<ex>utterance</ex> of false coin, or of forged notes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Vocal expression; articulation; speech.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At length gave <qex>utterance</qex> to these words.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Power or style of speaking; <as>as, a good
<ex>utterance</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They . . . began to speak with other tongues, as the Spirit gave
them <qex>utterance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Acts ii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, how unlike⟦br⟧
To that large <qex>utterance</qex> of the early gods!</q>
<rj><qau>Keats.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Utterance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Utterance
<hw>Ut"ter*ance</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>outrance</ets>. See
<er>Outrance</er>.]</ety> <def>The last extremity; the end; death;
outrance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Annibal forced those captives whom he had taken of our men to
skirmish one against another to the <qex>utterance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Utterer</ent>⟦br⟧
